"Yes, the Sault Ste. Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians (also known as the Sault Tribe) is actively and prominently involved in the cultural anthropology of medicine, particularly through the practice, preservation, and integration of Ojibwe (Anishinaabe) traditional medicine within their modern health systems.

saulttribehealth.com

Key Evidence of Involvement
Pioneering Traditional Medicine Program: Established in 1995, it was the first tribal traditional medicine program in the United States integrated into a tribal health delivery system (via Indian Health Services). It serves as a model for other tribes. 

saulttribehealth.com

Offers holistic Ojibwe traditional medicine services addressing spiritual, mental, physical, and emotional needs.
Includes consultations, diagnosis, and treatment by traditional practitioners using plants, herbs, and ceremonies.
Regularly holds healer clinics (e.g., with practitioners like Gerard Sagassige and Char Lewis).

Cultural Integration in Health Services: Their health division explicitly incorporates Anishinaabe ways of life, cultural preservation, and traditional healing alongside Western medicine. This reflects medical pluralism and culturally responsive care. 

saulttribehealth.com

Broader Cultural and Healing Initiatives:
Culture camps (e.g., Mary Murray Culture Camp) that include medicine picking and traditional knowledge transmission.
Programs linking traditional practices to behavioral health, addiction recovery (Wellbriety), and community wellness.
Emphasis on reclaiming cultural identity as a form of healing from historical trauma and assimilation. 

ictnews.org


Relation to Medical Anthropology
While the tribe itself is not an academic research institution, their work directly embodies and contributes to cultural anthropology of medicine (medical anthropology) themes:
Ethnomedicine and traditional healing systems.
Medical pluralism (integration of Indigenous and biomedical approaches).
Cultural constructions of health, illness, and healing.
Embodiment of cultural identity in health practices.
Decolonizing and community-driven health models.

Their program has been referenced in studies on Indigenous health, cultural healing, and historical trauma. Tribal members and collaborators sometimes participate in or are subjects of anthropological and public health research on these topics. 

pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

In summary: The Sault Tribe is a leader in applied, lived cultural anthropology of medicine through their longstanding Traditional Medicine Program and holistic health approach. This is not abstract academic study but active, community-embedded practice that anthropologists often document and learn from. For more details, visit their official health site (saulttribehealth.com) or contact the Traditional Medicine Program directly."
